msContents.summary: The Dialogue of St Anselm and the Virgin Mary is an account of the Passion, delivered by the Virgin Mary in response to questions from St Anselm. Liber Scintillarum is a thematically grouped collection of extracts from the Bible and the Church Fathers, translated into Early Modern Gaelic, and occasionally accompanied by commentary.

head.title: Jesus is buried; the disciples mourn him and recall what he meant to them; Mary wants to be buried with her son but John persuades her otherwise; they all return to Jerusalem; the sight of Mary moves the people to mourning; years later, to avenge Jesus's death, Vespasian and Titus besiege Jerusalem, slaughtering many and inflicting terrible famine; "the Jews" are scattered across the world and permanently deprived of sacred and secular authority
A colophon on the text's origins, translation, and transmission

note.p: Lib. Scint VII:1 (Matt. 21:22): Omnia quecumque petieritis in orationem credentes, accipietis.
Lib. Scint VII:2 (Luke 21:36): Vigilate itaque omni tempore orantes ut, regnum Dei digni, habeamini fugire omnia que futura sunt et stare ante Filium hominis.
At some point in the transmission, sabato ("sabbath") was misunderstood as samrad ("summer").
Lib. Scint VII:3 (Matt. 24:20): Orate autem ut non fíat fuga uestra hierne uel sabato.
Lib. Scint VII:6 (James 5:16): Orate in inuicem, ut saluimini. Multum enim ualit deprecatio iusti assidua.
Lib. Scint VII:7 (Prov. 15:29): Longe est Dominus ab impiis, et orationis iustorum exaudiet.
Lib. Scint VII:8 (Eccl. 7:9): Melior fines est orationis quam principium.
Lib. Scint VII:9 (Eccl. 18:23): Ante orationem praepara animam tuam, et noli esse quasi homo qui temptat Deum.
Lib. Scint VII:10 (Eccl. 35:1): Qui conseruat legem multiplicat orationem.

Lib. Scint. VII:27 (Isidore of Seville, Sententiae III:7.4): Oratio cordis est non labiorum; neque enim uerba deprecantes Deus intendit, sed orantes cor aspicit. Melius est autem cum silentio orare cordis, quam solis uerbis sine intuitu mentis. Quod si tacite quis orat et vox sileat, quamuis hominibus lateat, Deo latere non potest, qui conscientie presens est.
Lib. Scint. VIII:1 (Matt. 10:32): Omnis ergo qui confitebitur me coram hominibus, confitebor et ego eum coram Patrem meum qui in celis est, et reliqua.
Lib. Scint. VIII:2 (Rom. 10:10): Ore autem confessio fit in salutem.
Lib. Scint VIII:3 (James 5:16): Confitemini ergo alterutrum peccata uestra, et orate pro inuicem, ut saluimini.
Lib. Scint IV:1 (Matt. 11:29): Discite a me quia mitis sum et humilis corde, et inuenietis requiem animabus uestris.
Lib. Scint IV:2 (Isaiah 66:2): Ad quem respiciam, nisi ad humilem et quietum et trementem uerba mea.
Lib. Scint IV:3 (Luke 14:11, or 18:14): Omnes enim qui se exaltat humiliabitur, et qui se humilíat exaltabitur.

Lib. Scint IV:4 (1 Pet. 5:5–6): Omnes autem inuicem humilitatem insinuaete quia Deus superbis resistit, humilibus autem dat graciam. Humiliamini igitur sub potentis manu Dei, ut uos exaltat in tempore uisitacionis.
Lib. Scint IV:11 (Prov. 16:19): Melius est humiliare cum mitibus, quam diuidere spolia cum superbis.

Lib. Scint V:1 (Matt. 5:24): Si ergo offers munus tuum ad altare, et ibi recordatus fueris quia frater tuus habet aliquid aduersum te, relique ibi munus tuum ante altare, et uade prius reconciliare fratri tuo, et tunc ueniens offeris unus tuum.

Lib. Scint V:2 (Matt. 6:14–15): Si enim demiseretis hominibus peccata eorum, demittit uobis et Pater uester qui in celis est; si autem non demiseretis hominibus, nec Pater demittit uobis peccta uestra.
Arguably, "olcais" would make more sense here, given what precedes it, but the manuscript reading is clear.

Lib. Scint V:3 (Col. 3:13): Cum pacientia subportantes inuicem, et donantes uobismetipsis si quis aduersis aliquem habet querillam. Sicut Deus in Christo donauit uobis, ita et uos facite. Lib. Scint V:4 (Rom. 12:17): Nulli malum pro malo reddentes.
Prov. 15:16 (?). This does not appear in the section titled 'De Indulgencia' in Liber Scintillarum and the connection with the theme of forgiveness is not immediately clear.

Lib. Scint XI:1 (Matt. 19:29): Omnis qui reliquerit domus, uel fratres, aut sorores, aut patrem, aut matrem, aut uxorem, aut filius, aut agros propter nomen meum: centuplum accipiet et uitam aeternam possidebit.
Lib. Scint. VI:4 (James 4:4): Quicumque ergo uoluerit amicus esse seculi huius, inimicus Dei constituitur.
Lib. Scint. VI:1 (John 16:20): Amen amen dico uobis, quoniam uos plorabits et plangebitis, seculum autem gaudebit; uos tristis eritis, sed tristicia uestra in letitia ueniet.
Lib. Scint. VI:2 (Rom. 12:15): Gaudere cum gaudentibus, flere cum flentibus.
Lib. Scint. VI:3 (1 Cor. 7:30): Qui flent tamquam non flentes sint, et qui gaudent tamquam non gaudentes.
Lib. Scint. VI:4 (James 4:9): Miseri estote et lugite et plorate, risus uester in luctum conuertatur et gaudium in merore.
Lib. Scint. VI:5 (Prov. 14:13): Risus dolore miscebitur et extrema gaudii luctus occubat.
This is surely a mistake for "do chorp".
Lib. Scint. XII:1 (Matt. 10:28): Nolite timere eos qui occidunt corpus, animam autem occidere non possunt. Sed potius eum timere qui potest animam et corpus perdere in gehennam.
Lib. Scint. XII:2–3 (1 Pet. 2:17): In timore incolatus uestri tempus conuersamini. Deum timete, regem honorificate
Lib. Scint. XII:4 (1 Pet. 3:2): Considerantes in timore castam conuersationem uestram.
The medieval translator seems to have misunderstood "abba" (father) as "son".
Lib. Scint. XII:5 (Rom. 8:15): Non enim accepistis spiritum seruitutis iterum in timore, sed accepistis spiritum adoptionis filiorum, in quo clamamus abba pater.
Lib. Scint. XII:7 (Eccl. 1:16): Initium sapientiae timor Domini.

p.hi: Source unknown; possibly commentary on previous entry.

note.p: Lib. Scint. XIII:1 (Luke 20:34–36): Filii seculi huius nubunt et traduntur ad nuptias; illi uero digni habentur seculo illo et resurrectionem ex mortuis neque nubent, neque ducunt uxores, neque enim ultra mori potuerunt, aequalis enim angelis sunt, et filii sunt Dei, sum sint filii resurrectionis.
Lib. Scint. XIII:2 (1 Cor. 7:32 or 34): Virgo que innupta est cogitat que Domini sunt, quomodo placeat Deo.
Lib. Scint. VIII:4 (Prov. 28:13): Qui abscondit scelera sua, non dirigetur; qui autem confessus fuerit et reliquerit, misericordiam consequitur.

Lib. Scint. VIII:5 (1 John 1:8–9): Si dixerimus quia peccatum non abemus, ipse nos seducimus, et ueritas in nobis non est. Si autem confiteamur peccata nostra, fidelis et iustus est, ut remittat nobis peccata et mundet nos ab omni peccato.
Lib. Scint. VIII:6 (Sir. 4:31): Non confunderis confiteri peccata tua, ne subicias te homine peccato.
Lib. Scint. VIII:7 (Sir. 17:27): Ante morte confitere, uiuus sanus confiteberis, et laudabis Dominum, et gloriaberis in miserationibus illius.
Lib. Scint. VIII:8 (Origen, On Leviticus 9:8): Si dixeris peccata prior, exaudiet te Dominus tamquam populum sanctum.
Lib. Scint. VIII:9 (Augustine, On the Gospel of John XII:13): Confessio omnium malorum inicium est operum bonorum.
Lib. Scint. VIII:15 ("Ambrose"; source unknown): Neque enim adhibere ei potest remedium cuius est uulnus occultum.
Lib. Scint. IX:1 (Matt. 3:2, but the speaker is John the Baptist): Penitentiam agite, adpropinquauit enim regnum caelorum.
Lib. Scint. IX:2 (Acts 2:38): Penitentiam agite, et baptizetur unusquisque uestrum, et accipietis donum Spiritus Sancti.
Lib. Scint. IX:3 (Rom. 2:7): His quidem qui, secundum penitentiam boni operis, gloriam et honorem et incorruptionem querentibus, uitam aeternam.
Lib. Scint. IX:4 (Sir. 20:4): Bonum est corruptum manifestare paenitentiam; sic enim effugit uoluntarie peccatum.
Lib. Scint. IX:6 (Sir 5:5) (?): De propicíato peccatorum noli esse sine metu, neque adicias peccatum super peccato.
Lib. Scint. IX:7 (Sir. 5:8): Ne tardis conuerti ad Dominum, et ne differas de die in diem.
Lib. Scint. IX:8 (Sir 8:6) (?): Ne dispicias hominem auertente se a peccato; memento quoniam omnes in corruptione sumus.
Lib. Scint. IX:9 (Sir. 12:3) (?): Altissimus hodio habit peccatores et misertus est penitentibus.
There is a punctus over the "r".

The "-aib" is actually part of the main text. The main text originally read "ditreabachaib" and the caret mark for the insertion ("eter na ditrubac") is between "-ch-" and "-aib". Adding this multiple word insertion to the word thus represented solely by "-aib" would have added significant complexity to the TEI markup and so the "-aib" is being treated as an insertion into the insertion instead.
A caret mark possibly appears here but an attempt seems to have been made to erase it. There is no material in the margins for insertion.
The word "capitel" is in a different, more reddish ink. The hand appears to be the same.
There is a trace of what could be a lenition marker over the "m" of "mac" but it is unclear as well as unexpected.
A caret mark has been placed here but a much more cogent location for the insertion is to be found later in the line, where a second caret mark has been placed.
Psalm 74:19
The rest of the manuscript line is taken up with a pen-drawn cloud shape. This is presumably merely intended as a filler.

An insertion point appears here. The scribe apparently intends to move "millsi" to follow "reamra" (as per Atkinson 1887: 55). This would imply the deletion of the phrase, "agus glac do mecnaib", that follows, which may have been added via eye-skip. However, as no deletion is shown explicitly, and as there is nothing ungrammatical about the text as first inscribed, it is being retained.
